60|$|Jack {{was never}} called out again for active service, {{and lived in}} the {{neighborhood}} of Southampton until the end of his long life, buying a small estate there, when, at the death of Mr. Anthony, the handsome fortune which the cloth merchant had made came to his daughter, subject <b>to</b> <b>an</b> <b>annuity</b> <b>to</b> Mrs. Anthony, who took up her abode {{for the rest of her}} life with her son-in-law, her daughter, and their children. For many years Colonel Stilwell sat in parliament as member for Southampton, and maintained a warm friendship with his ancient commander until the death of the latter, in 1735.|$|R
